  "output": "Good picture of the codebase. No frontend yet — pure Python engine. Here's what I found:\n\n---\n\n## Performance Analysis\n\n### No issues found\n- **N+1 queries**: No DB layer yet — engine is pure in-memory. Flag this for when PostgreSQL is added: `GameState.players` dict lookups will need batch fetching.\n- **React re-renders**: No frontend yet.\n\n---\n\n### Issues found\n\n#### 1. Import inside a loop — `game_engine.py:32`\n\n```python\nfor role in ROLE_ORDER:\n    from core.models import IncomingShipment  # ← runs 4x every create_game()\n```\n\nPython caches module objects but `from x import y` still does a dict lookup + name binding each iteration. Move to top of file.\n\n```python\n# game_engine.py top\nfrom core.models import GameConfig, GamePhase, GameState, PlayerRole, PlayerState, ROLE_ORDER, IncomingShipment\n```\n\n---\n\n#### 2. Double iteration over `incoming_shipments` — `order_processor.py:7-13`\n\n```python\narrived = sum(s.quantity for s in ps.incoming_shipments if s.arrives_in_rounds == 1)  # pass 1\nps.incoming_shipments = [\n    IncomingShipment(quantity=s.quantity, arrives_in_rounds=s.arrives_in_rounds - 1)\n    for s in ps.incoming_shipments\n    if s.arrives_in_rounds > 1  # pass 2, +allocates new objects\n]\n```\n\nTwo passes + new `IncomingShipment` object per surviving shipment per round. Pydantic v2 models are mutable by default — mutate in place:\n\n```python\ndef advance_shipments(state: GameState) -> GameState:\n    for ps in state.players.values():\n        arrived = 0\n        surviving = []\n        for s in ps.incoming_shipments:\n            if s.arrives_in_rounds == 1:\n                arrived += s.quantity\n            else:\n                s.arrives_in_rounds -= 1\n                surviving.append(s)\n        ps.inventory += arrived\n        ps.incoming_shipments = surviving\n    return state\n```\n\nSingle pass, zero new object allocations.\n\n---\n\n#### 3. `incoming_orders` list never consumed — `order_processor.py:72` + `game.py:38`\n\n```python\nupstream_ps.incoming_orders.append(order_qty)  # appended every round\n```\n\n`incoming_orders` is defined as `list[int]` on `PlayerState` but **nothing ever reads or clears it**. After 26 rounds, each player has 26 stale entries. This is both a memory growth issue and likely a bug — the data is dead weight.\n\nEither remove the field if it's unused, or consume and clear it:\n\n```python\n# If it's meant to track orders received for display:\ndef place_orders(state: GameState) -> GameState:\n    for i, role in enumerate(roles):\n        ...\n        if i < len(roles) - 1:\n            upstream_ps.incoming_orders.clear()  # or replace with just the current round\n            upstream_ps.incoming_orders.append(order_qty)\n```\n\n---\n\n#### 4. `is_round_complete()` recomputes set every call — `game.py:56`\n\n```python\ndef is_round_complete(self) -> bool:\n    active_roles = {role for role, ps in self.players.items() if not ps.is_ai}  # new set each call\n    return active_roles.issubset(self.orders_this_round.keys())\n```\n\n`is_ai` flags don't change mid-game. If this is called on every `submit_order()`, cache it:\n\n```python\n@cached_property\ndef human_roles(self) -> frozenset[PlayerRole]:\n    return frozenset(role for role, ps in self.players.items() if not ps.is_ai)\n\ndef is_round_complete(self) -> bool:\n    return self.human_roles.issubset(self.orders_this_round.keys())\n```\n\nNote: Pydantic v2 supports `model_config = ConfigDict(...)` — you'll need `from functools import cached_property` and may need to handle cache invalidation if players ever change post-init.\n\n---\n\n#### 5. `round_cost()` duplicates `accrue_costs` logic with different constants — `game.py:42` vs `order_processor.py:86-90`\n\n```python\n# game.py:42 — uses module-level constants\ndef round_cost(self) -> float:\n    return self.inventory * HOLDING_COST_PER_UNIT + self.backlog * BACKLOG_COST_PER_UNIT\n\n# order_processor.py:88 — uses config values\ncost = ps.inventory * state.config.holding_cost + ps.backlog * state.config.backlog_cost\n```\n\nIf someone creates a `GameConfig` with non-default costs, `round_cost()` returns wrong numbers. Remove `round_cost()` or delegate:\n\n```python\ndef round_cost(self, config: \"GameConfig\") -> float:\n    return self.inventory * config.holding_cost + self.backlog * config.backlog_cost\n```\n\n---\n\n### Summary table\n\n| # | File | Line | Severity | Type |\n|---|------|------|----------|------|\n| 1 | `game_engine.py` | 32 | Low | Import in loop |\n| 2 | `order_processor.py` | 7–13 | Medium | Double iteration + object churn |\n| 3 | `order_processor.py` | 72 | **High** | Unbounded list growth (likely bug) |\n| 4 | `game.py` | 56 | Low | Redundant set construction |\n| 5 | `game.py` | 42 | **High** | Logic divergence / correctness bug |\n\nItems 3 and 5 are correctness bugs masquerading as perf issues. Fix those first.\n",
